{
  "doc_id": "41914",
  "text": "Also, mutations in clock genes or changes in their expression levels and rhythmicity were observed in various cancer types in animal models, human cell models, patient samples and population based studies. Additionally, the circadian clock regulates cell cycle, DNA damage responses, ageing and metabolism through different mechanisms. Hence, altered circadian rhythms may also lead to impaired regulation of these processes, leading to tumourigenesis [CITATION_1] .",
